,Recommended,296070,31947797,Posted: 25 May,all,jonathan.s,"I suppose I'd recommend.The biggest problem with MIND: Path to Thalamus is that there's no one quality that really makes it stand out in the 'indie walking simulator' genre. This means it's easy to compare it to other games, saying things 'Dear Esther had a better story' or 'Antichamber had better puzzles' or 'Vanishing of Ethan Carter looked better'. All of these statements are true. MIND is slow, cold, and lonely. I remember almost every level bugging me in some small way, like,  'I can't set this down exactly where I want, it rolls away...' or, 'why do I have to walk so far?' or 'really, I didn't get the timing right?' And this is why I'm conflicted in my recommendation. Because of all these issues, MIND isn't especially fun toplay.But that doesn't mean you should avoid MIND: Path to Thalamus. Theexperience- the atmosphere, the lighting, the slow pace - was surprisingly immersive. I found myself getting into the mindset of the game, feeling the protagonist's isolation, which made the experience powerful and memorable. So, as an atmospheric walking simulator, I think it succeeded.I'm not recommending MIND 'to have fun', but I'm recommending it as an interesting experience for fans of the genre."
