,Not Recommended,296070,32752386,Posted: 24 June,all,C1awed,"Pros:  It's very pretty.Con:I didn't do too much reading about the plot of the game beforehand- I never do.  I got the connection to the brain/psychology from the title, but once playing it, there was nothing, even in the narration, to firmly connect what I was doing to any greater plot.  I travelled point-to-point mostly because it's completely linear.It seemed like the writers couldn't decide if the narrator was an outside voice who knew what was going on, or the protagonists inner, tormented memories.  I wish they'd stuck with the latter, and left context to explain the formor.  As a result, the game felt like a series of disconnected puzzles - and if you missed too many of the easily-overlooked narration points, you were even *more* lost.The puzzles themselves were nothing more than ""Find the arbitrarty set piece to stick a colored ball in to open the next door"".  The game really felt like the devs wanted to make a walking simulator, but instead, had to stick a game in it.  As a result, the puzzles are sheer repetition and they do not fit logically with the world - something that might have been explained by the plot, had there been any of that.I didn't even realize we were supposed to be journeying towards ""consciousness"" until I paused the game and read the chapter titles.There is no save function - at all.  There is no loading screen, or indication of what chapter you're on.  If you need to step away from the game for sometime, you get to guess at which chapter to restart from, loading the game over and over until you figure out where you were.   The loading screen is just a fade to black, with no text or sound, and they're so long that several times I thought my game had locked up.Every chapter is available from the moment you install it, so if you just want to play the prologue and the end, go for it.  Which is good, because if you get stuck on a puzzle - or stuck in the world - you can simply advance to the next chapter.  You don't miss anything doing this, which is bad.Physics in the game is both realistic, and your worst enemy.  The UI and controls are sort of intuitive, but it's hard to tell what actions will make your character drop their ball - again, your only item and one of only two interactions - and what will perform the move you want.  Item boundary boxes do not match up with their graphics all the time, so in puzzles that require throwing the item, or rolling it to a destination, you can wind up throwing yourself against invisible walls to find the actual interaction point.Invisible walls, after a while, also become the games only boundary.  At several points I could clearly see my destination straight in front of me, headed towards it, and was abruptly forced back into the skinner box by an invisible wall.  A few times, the devs made an attempt to indicate a boundary; at others, your space abruptly ends in the middle of a grassy field.  At least give me a fence or something!There are also several glitches.  At more than one point, I fell through the floor and walls, getting stuck and forcing a reload from the start of the subsection.  I was able to skip entire puzzles on one level by simply walking along the edge of a cliff.   Many of the subtitles were garbled, or, in a few cases, missing entirely - as someone who depends on subtitles, it meant I missed out on even *more* of the nonexistant plot.I paid $1.50 for this game and feel ripped off."
,Recommended,296070,11589602,"Posted: 7 August, 2014",all,Jamyjet,"One of the best indie games i've played this year, it's an absolute must for any fans of indie, adventure or puzzle games. The game looks amazing and the music suits the dark yet colourful world that the protagonist traverses. I've heard people criticise the narration of the game, but I really can't complain as i found the story very ingaging and it kept me wondering what was going to happen next. The games biggest downside, like many indie games like it is probably it's length. Don't expect to get a full 8-10 hour experience out of it like you might with a AAA title, but the 4-5 hours you do get will be incredibly unforgettable. There are also some not story related achievements to go back for and a chance to speed run through some of those tantalisingly difficult puzzles.Overall, Mind: Path to Thalamus is a great gaming experience, with great game mechanics, superb graphics and an engaging story to keep you occupied for hours.For more information and gameplay footage, check out my walkthrough here -https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TSWSoZhEIGw&list=UUI6wSDrFxD8RSk96qFp3oMA"
