76561197995133463,Recommended,296070,13702518,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,Drown In Your Lies,"This game contains a great dichotomy between the self-satisfaction of a puzzle game with the burden that you (as the main character) are a terrible person. I felt punished, redeemed, guilty, responsible, attached, and devoid of what he was trying to accomplish and/or escape from. It's one of the few puzzle games where the narrative is as compelling and rewarding as the puzzles themselves. Benefits greatly from a willingness to listen and empathise, so definitely play with the sound on. The environments are colorful and varied, and the last few levels in particular are ""stop and look at the skybox"" beautiful.It's only a few hours long, and not overly difficult, so you shouldn't worry about not being able to reach the end. Very much recommended for people who enjoy puzzle games, or who want a short but noteworthy experience.I don't write many reviews, but this game resonated enough with me that I felt the need to put those feelings in writing."
76561197979563731,Recommended,296070,14250940,"Posted: 30 January, 2015",all,Chromatose,"This really is something special.  It's also clearly had a lot of love and care lavished on it, and it shows in the numerous updates since the game has launched to address criticism, and fine-tune the gameplay mechanics.Mind: Path To Thalamus is a really difficult game to nail down.  It could be erroneously referred to as either a puzzle game or (ugh) a ""walking simulator"", but neither would do the experience justice.  Sure, violence is conspicuously absent, and the main mechanical thrust of the game is solving some very clever (but never obtuse or frustrating) puzzles.  However, the game feels like much more than this, due to a very clear narrative thread that ties the various parts of the experience together, making a variety of visually stunning yet disparate environments form parts of an epic journey towards the Thalamus of the title.Of particular note is the frozen tsunami towards the end, which stands out as one of the most visually striking game environments in recent memory, although Mind is full of surreal and mind-bogglingly beautiful environments.  You'll traverse huge expanses of dreamlike field, navigate impossible geometry, fight a behemoth hundreds of feet high, and alter the environment itself.In spite of various criticisms, I also feel the narrative deserves praise for touching on the themes of bereavement and family tragedy in a manner notably absent of sensationalism or tokenism.  You never feel like the game is feeding you sentimentality, which it easily could have.  Although the voice-acting can come across as rather melodramatic, the story being told feels low-key and relatable.All in all, this is a fantastic purchase - a visual tour-de-force with finely honed puzzle-solving gameplay, good story, and a beautiful licensed soundtrack.  Recommended without a shadow of a doubt."
