,Recommended,296070,32581807,Posted: 19 June,all,Vinrafel,"Video Reviewhttps://youtu.be/rhzdq8sHbSoQuick InfoMind: Path to Thalamusreally succeeds in its holistic narrative approach. The puzzles were okay, but the interesting ones only came at the end of the game with much of the initial portion being a slog. If you want to see an example of a game that threads its story throughout all of its elements, then this is the title for you. If you’re looking for a good puzzler or a easy, relaxing walking simulator then you should turn away now.Path to Thalamuswas as frustrating at times as it was interesting. Admittedly, it is a pretty good buy for the price.For a more in-depth review see the video above or read the review at:Vinrafel"
,Recommended,296070,19690301,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,Proxykon,"MIND: Path to Thalamus is a narrative puzzle experience.Design & ArtThe most obvious strongpoint of this game is its design and art. When I first played the game, it really drew me in instantly. I have never seen more beautifully crafted worlds and places in any game I played. Fitting color palettes, light and ethereal music support the visuals of the game positively.ControlsThe controls are pretty straightforward; if you played any shooter in the last century, you’ll have no problems whatsoever. You play from First-Person-perspective.Sound & MusicSounddesign is well managed and fitting. The music supports the game, feels well placed in concordance with most of the visuals and enhanced the gameplay.GameplayThe puzzles (which are the fundamental basis of this game) are forgiving enough at the beginning and get procedurally harder during the game. You can solve them with pure wit, sometimes you need trial and error (which, in my opinion, is rather a last resort than a viable solution to a problem). I have to note that most of the puzzles also require a LOT of walking. Solving a puzzle for the first time will take some duration and tenacity, since there is no running option in the game.WeakpointsThe game seems rather simplistic in its design and gameplay which positively supports the game, but that same simplicity also mortifies “Path to Thalamus”.The narrative part of the game is a very interesting topic (human psychology of loss and grief), yet its execution feels shallow and amiss. During the game, you rather scrape than plunge into said topics. The narrative picks you up at the beginning, but loses itself during later parts of the game. The voice acting feels cringeworthy at times and didn’t make me feel immersed enough. I guess the common disliking of the narrative part of the game lead to its near complete removal of the story in the “enhanced version” of the game (it is optional now, you don’t need to listen to the story). One of its weakpoints is fairly common among story-driven games: Replayability is completely out of the question, just like in Frictional Games’ “Amnesia” and “Penumbra”-series.And speaking of the devil, the “enhanced version” of the game (which was introduced recently) is the biggest thorn in my side. Holy hell. I bought and played the game before the new version and liked it to a certain degree. The “enhanced version” really ruined it for me. The game now runs more badly than before, I get way less Fps than before on the same settings, yet my hardware hasn’t changed. My PC fulfills all of the recommended settings.Not only that. At the same time, the graphics are now worse than before! How could this happen? The game is now more colorful than before, contrasts are higher (to a degree in which I couldn’t even see in the darkness, where before I could), my native resolution is now not supported by standard (What the frick?!), handling of objects feels worse and the ending and certain puzzles have been completely reworked.Concluding ThoughtsI really enjoyed the journey through someones elses mind. I can toss aside bad storylines by simply ignoring them. If you are a person, who enjoys beautifully crafted worlds and light puzzle solving, I urge you to get this game and install the old version of it (game options under steam -> betas -> old_mind). I cannot and will not support the new version of the game, since it feels worse than the unenhanced version. Don’t let yourself get fooled by this game's looks, while being beautiful, its narrative feels unstructured and messy. A real shame, because I want to love the game on both of these aspects. Yet I still enjoyed the game to a certain degree.Enjoy with caution. Do not play the new version if you want a decent experience with the game."
76561198008006340,Recommended,296070,11820266,"Posted: 22 August, 2014",all,The Slammin' Salmon,"Really sweet game. Awesome story, all the way to the end. Neat puzzles, too. It felt like Portal, but instead of Companion Cubes, you have Rolling Stones."
,Not Recommended,296070,25367380,"Posted: 5 September, 2016",all,"Fancy, Schmancy!","I wanted to love this game but just couldn't. Yes, it's beautiful. The strength of this game is in its dreamy, neoclassical landscapes that feel like you're wandering through an oil painting. But you can experience most of that beauty in a screenshot. In game, it feels hollow, stretched over an obtuse, lukewarm story and halfhearted puzzle elements that never quite reach Talos Principle levels of satisfaction.The biggest detriment, though, is the sound design. In a game that should feel immersive, the silences are glaringly awkward, punctuated by crashes and screeches set to jumpscare volumes. Meanwhile, the sparse dialogue sound like a mouse monologuing from inside a tin can. They didn't feel like surrealist choices to me. They just felt underproduced.If you go into this game anticipating a well rendered walking simulator instead of a story-driven first-person puzzler, you'll probably get more enjoyment from the game than I did. I don't regret the purchase, but I wish the game had matched its visuals with a better narrative and gameplay."
