,Not Recommended,296070,24025196,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,EsotericMemeticPoetic,"MIND: Path to Thalamus might be described as a ""Walking simulator"" type game, but I'd place it more in the ""Puzzle Platformer"" genre; that's fine, not exactly what I was expecting, but still a style that I enjoy. The problem is that it doesn't do much with either element of that genre: barely any platforming, and the puzzles--for the most part--aren't very puzzling.The game manages to have beatiful environments, that you can't explore, and a nice ambient soundtrack, that you don't hear often. This kind of makes sense within the constraints of the plot, because (SPOILER that's given away by the title anyway): you're withing the main character's mind. I'm not sure about most people, but I don't hear music 24/7 in my brain; the invisible walls with lush scenery is still irksome--I'm not free to visit all the beauty that I see behind these narrow walls, and paths so obvious they could almost be described as ""on rails.""By far the most egregious transgression of the game, though, is the narration. The story is actually quite interesting: it has good character development, wonderful visual representations of the plot (all the visual metaphors and motifs are excellent), and an intriguing concept (representing the subconscious mind of the character). The narration ruins all of this; the exposition is helpful, but felt rushed at the end cutscene (as if not enough had come through during the game) and most of it was telling the audience how to interpret the gameplay or cutscenes as part of the plot instead of just letting us make those connections.If this was a free game that I played on some website while I was bored, I could forgive it and say that it's worth a play as a kind of timewaster. On steam for $9, I can't in good conscience recommend it to others and say that it's a good investment. I see a lot of potential in the devs and want them to receive the support, both financially and motivationally, to continue honing their skill, but I'd rather fund a new game than misdirect people to support them through this one."
