,Recommended,296070,11992451,"Posted: 5 September, 2014",all,Memph,"------Intro------Mind: Path to Thalamus is a game very much like Myst, but at least you can see what is happening this time, rather than walking aimlessly till you come across something useful. No! Not this game; in the world of making games more 'accessible' it's nice to be able to play a game which challenges your intelligence. To be honest, this is first game in a long while which I had to look at a walkthrough for (admittedly for a small thing I overlooked).---------Set-up---------If you were hoping for an options menu to rival Borderlands 2, then I am afraid to inform you that is not the case. The options they do include are;> Subtitles> Resolution - All the standard types> V-sync> Windowed/Fullscreen> Post-processing - Low, medium, high, ultra - Would have like to have seen more options here for individual effects.> Draw distance - low, medium, high, hugeUnfortunately there are no rebinding of keys - admittedly there are only 6 buttons, but I'm very much a esdf guy, so this was a bummer-------------The Game-------------The basics are very simple, walk around putting balls in spots to solve a puzzle. It is a text book definition of a walking simulator and it uses incredible art and design to keep you preoccupied during the long distances. From the comments I have heard the voice acting was obnoxious; but I felt it really set the tone for the characters grief as well as keeping it interesting during the puzzles.The art design is wonderful, epic skyboxes, detailed yet minimalistic landscapes and brilliant lighting.But I have a couple of complaints:One - Night mode ruins the beautiful colours this game has during day/time modesTwo - The balls are in the way, especially the glowing one, they could be at your side, not directly in front of the screenThree - White. Just too much white.These do seem minor, but a large portion of the game involves night time mechanics it would be great to keep it, but not to the extent to which it was used. The balls also obstruct your vision which is needed in this type of game to appreciate and understand your surroundings.In quite a few sections of the game it gets… Not horror-like, but a lot of threat, using various sound effects and environmental changes to compete the effect. So if that ain't your thing you might be rather discomforted when experiencing it for the first time.The main fault of the game is… Time. Spent. Walking.In portal there is no walking, there is limited space with portals leading to the next, and the next, and the next; often in quick succession. In this game you spend way too much time walking - going to and coming back from a dead end takes a lot of time making you regret going down there in the first place, and making you less willing to explore. Some puzzles require set up time which forces you to travel to the other end of the map for no logical reason; incredibly annoying if you mess it up and have to try again, and some levels are just plain huge, punishing mistakes through boredom.--------------Conclusion--------------Overall I feel this is a great gem of a title which you might finish in about 5 hours. If you can get over possible frustration with long walks then I would go for it, oh, and the soundtrack is beautiful; works so well with the feel of the game. I feel these developers had an idea and stuck with their guns, and it really paid off.This is Wilfred McCabe signing off, good night."
