,Recommended,296070,13873374,"Posted: 6 January, 2015",all,Audeez,"As a game and an interactive experience, Mind: Path to Thalamus succeeds in being one of the more successful attempts to bring logical puzzle play to a surreal environment. As a metaphorical narrative, it leaves something to be desired.The game play of Mind is simple, in order to proceed you have to bring these blue tumbleweed things to various locations in order to manipulate the environmental aspects of day/night, weather, and time in order to unlock the path forward. Utilizing a gradual learning curve that still offers a challenge, Mind starts you off with one element at a time - for instance: teaching you that sometimes an object you need may be visible only at night and then having you figure out how to acquire this object without sacrificing some other aspect of your progression - before introducing multiple elements at once By the end of the game you're very much thinking 4th dimensionally about things, but even the head-scratchingest of puzzles were logical in the end. Even at my most frustrated, I never thought ""that's a stupid solution"" and instead was more apt to berate myself for not having noticed it sooner.More than just eye candy. Mind utilizes its surreal environments to full effect, with puzzles involving everything from reflections to portals, and gravity. Sadly however the story seems virtually divorced from the game play aside from the its heavy handed ending levels. Unlike Papo & Yo (another surreal adventure puzzler) Mind says too much too often and relies too much on narration and all-too-obvious symbols to achieve its metaphor. The gameplay could easily be read as part of the main character's coma-induced journey, but it rarely relates directly to the subjects and experiences the narrator talks about. Add to this the fairly amateur voice acting and VERY uneven dialogue volume (with no option to adjust) and Mind's narrative experience fell a little flat with me, feeling extraneous at best and pretentious at worst.Overall the game was an enjoyable experience however and for the environments and puzzles alone is worth checking out. There are some interesting ideas at work here that I felt justified my time spent with the game."
76561198067292767,Recommended,296070,14442588,"Posted: 12 February, 2015",all,tanis0,"Mind: Path to Thalamus is visually stunning and worth playing for that reason alone. However, some of the puzzles are tedious such as searching a large area when you can only see about 3 feet in front of you and others are frustrating, such as slowly moving while trying to dodge objects from the sky only to get repeatedly crushed. Also, the story isn't great and the voice acting is worse. The game appears to have been deeloped by a Spanish game studio so presumably this is a translated version, but it feels like someone's buddy volunteered to do the voice -- it just doesn't match the professional value of the visuals. Still, it is one of the prettiest looking games I've played in some time."
,Recommended,296070,14428210,"Posted: 10 February, 2015",all,Locksheon,"I'm not going to pretend I fully understand the story or it's resolution, however, the game is absolutely, breathtakingly beautiful.   It reminded me a lot of Myst / Riven,  but with full control over your character.The game is basically a journey through a man's mind.  I believe he and his father were former 'storm chasers'.  Tragedy strikes, leaving a list of hurt, regret, and confusion.    Throughout the levels, you seem to be 'repairing' damaged parts of his memories and/or neural pathways.  You are treated to dialogue along the way that explains this history of the protagonist, but toward the end, things get really confusing, and I wasn't able to fully understand the finale.  The voice acting is ok, but at times it comes off a little cheesy.All-in-all, I would totally recommend this game to anyone who loves puzzle games such as Myst.   I paid 7 dollars for the game, and felt it was just the right amount since I was able to  beat the entire game in about 4-5 hours.Go to my profile and check out my screenshots of the game!"
76561198105355539,Recommended,296070,14552664,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,austin.mckenzie,"Epic, Entertaining, Enjoyable:It helps to have a video card. That said, after I turned all the effects down to minimum standards, the game operated quite smoothly with only moderate drops in frame rate.Also while carrying the blue tumbleweeds, you will occassionally have to hold a tumbleweed up above your head while you walk forward with it to avoid tripping over said tumbleweed and have it roll away on you. Picking up and manipulating the tumbleweeds is a core gameplay mechanic and I just wished the developers had smoothed it out a bit more. The game is well designed but just gets choppy every once in a while. It is also helpful to remember that this game was crafted by just a handful of dudes.Overall, the flow of gameplay was very organic and the environments were forgiving enough to allow the player to get creative in their problem solving. That is not to say that there are multiple solutions to puzzles; I don't think there are, just that the game will frequently require you to think out of the box and understand how the blue tumbleweeds might interact with the level. Intuitive, logical and very fun to play."
,Recommended,296070,15708759,"Posted: 5 May, 2015",all,Thovarin,"Mind: Path to Thalamus game has wormed its way into my mind. Its atmospheric, emotional impact is its strongest selling point for me. This physic's based puzzler had me hungry to complete it, which I did in a day. Be aware that this title was made by an indie studio, which is both obvious and an accomplishment. For the amount of developers involved, it shows a great deal of thought and foresight. It is clearly a labor of love for most involved, and I felt rewarded by that.If you're looking for blockbuster polish and explosive cinematics, this is probably not the game for you. If you love puzzlers; atmospheric, surreal environments; and you are used to playing indie titles, this is right up your alley, and I couldn't recommend it more. I don't know if I'll ever replay it strictly for the gameplay, since the solutions are obvious and easily achievable once you know the answer, but the feels and sensations that this game offer make it well worth a revisit. Also, the credits hint at the story of how and why this game was made, so sit through them if you enjoyed your experience. It definitely adds to the tale told.Well done, Carlos Coronado et al. I look forward to your next release and hope it is as gratifying as Mind: Path to Thalamus!"
