,Recommended,296070,13505156,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,Nite_Traveler,"It's amazing to me that a game so beautiful in its design and creative in its puzzles can be so deeply marred by the writing and voice acting. Earlier on in the game, I had dismissed the comments in reviews that detracted the voice acting, thinking ""it's not so bad"". But now, having finally finished the game, I understand. While I think the story itself is very interesting, the way it is told and not shown ruins the execution. The narration seems to assume that the player is not clever enough to understand what is going on unless it is painstakingly explained by way of pretentious voice-acting. At times, it even seems to be self-deprecating, as if aware of some of its own flaws. The ending is particularly guilty of this, which very nearly robs the player of any satisfaction to be found in the resolution of the story. In particular, the comments about the ""evil ball of death"" and the voice-swapping were sheer moments of face-palm for me. So despite the fact that I found this game incredible on several other levels, it left me on a sour note. Am I implying I could have done a better job with the writing? Absolutely not, and I have to stress that I commend the creators of this game for such an excellent story and concept. I just feel that the game would have nothing to lose and everything to gain by simply removing the narration entirely. Perhaps this could even be a settings option to just disable it. For bonus points, the game could ""show"" a bit more of the story along the way in place of telling it.Now that my complaints are out of the way, I can get on to writing about what an amazing game this is, on every other level. Based on the concept, design, and gameplay, it could have been the ideal game for me. I was overjoyed to find a game based on the intersection of the exploration of consciousness and psychology with fantastical landscapes and locations - something like that is right up my alley. And indeed, that's what this is, and it's executed wonderfully. Many of the level designs, art concepts and effects that you'll experience here are truly stunning, and I found this to be even more true as I approached the end. While the puzzle mechanics could have used a bit more diversity, the different ways they are combined in the more challenging puzzles keeps things fresh and enjoyably mind-bending. The gameplay is at its most satisfying when it nudges you to think in new ways in order to solve different types of puzzles. And the locations are perpetually screenshot-worthy, always vast and mysterious, a joy to explore. Each of these elements are incredibly well-executed and provide a unique experience.I spent about 5 hours here and would gladly enjoy another playthrough someday. I don't feel the flaws in the game come close to eclipsing the things it does well, so I can only click the recommend button, and hope you enjoy this game with appropriately adjusted expectations for the narration."
