76561198069735211,Recommended,296070,14784682,"Posted: 7 March, 2015",all,DaHotFuzz,"Mind: Path to Thalamus is a first-person, exploratation, puzzle game that focuses on changing weather and time to shape the environment around you.  The story, not so much engrossing, is interesting to a point.  Voice acting was more or less average.  Soundtrack was serene and elegantly composed.  What made this little gem worth playing through was the scenery and overall atmosphere.  Excellently done on the graphics, simple but beautiful all the same.  Puzzles range from fairly obvious to moderately difficult depending on your experience.My big peeve with the game is regarding one of the last levels.  I can't really explain it without spoiling anything, but you have to execute the puzzle a certain way or else you can't finish it.  I spent over an hour without making any progress because after I solved part of the puzzle, the level no longer let me change some of the weather.  It's also important to note that in this particular level, after having solved a portion of it, I could not reverse it.  I had to start over after watching a walkthrough.  Furthermore, this level from what I gathered was the ONLY one in the game where if you messed up, you had no choice but to start over.  I understand and appreciate it when puzzle games don't take you by the hand and help you every step of the way but with this case, it was incredibly frustrating not knowing a mistake you made in the puzzle was irreversible.7/10"
76561198045606340,Recommended,296070,14301341,"Posted: 2 February, 2015",all,Cortano,"Before I get to criticize this game let's first talk about what you get for the 13€, or whatever amount of whatever currency you pay for this title.The Steam description of the game reads that it is ""a First Person Puzzler that throws you into a fantastic and surreal environment"". Well, I can't argue with that this statement describes the game perfectly. The environment varies from an absolutely still watercovered plain of sand, over an autumn forrest, to a giant frozen ocean and while doing so, looks absolutely gorgeous. The graphics and the overall look of the game are, for it to be built on the Unreal Engine and for it to be an indie title, flawless. There are no edges or blank spots, no bitmap sky or background. If you are looking for beautiful titles Mind is the game to buy.But let us stop praisig Path to Thalamus for the one thing we know it does right.The Steam description furthermore claims, that you are able to ""bend the natural elements to your will in order to progress"". That is only partialy true. The description suggests that you are able to bend 6 different ""Elements"", the trailer however only mentions 5: Mist, Rain, Past, Day and Night. I say there are only 4, which are: Mist, Rain, the seasons (past and present) and the daytime (day and night). However the puzzles still are rich and unique for the elements are one by one added througout the game, playing together and making it more complicated to progress. To make it even harder the game does not give you any hints whatsoever exept the very basic movement controlls, so you actually have to figure out how everything works by yourself. The puzzles themselves are challenging though not unsolvable if being thought about long enough.Still there is one big flaw in the game which makes the gameplay far less enjoyable.I'm talking about the leveldesign. The levels are almost pompous, to big for them to feature puzzles. You have to walk for actual minutes to get to one point of the map to do something, then run back into the opposite direction to do somethig else, which is especially frustrating if what you are doing fails and you have to start over. However I can understand the choice for the dimensions. The levels needed to be big for the artistic effect to kick in, otherwise it would have either looked like a ton of hills, with all the elements cramped together in the middle, or it woud not have been big enough for the game to look this beautiful. I guess it's as they say: Beauty comes with a price.Let us now leave the surface behind us and get to the core of every good game: the story.Mind: Path to Thalamus only features one character, a father who was knocked into a coma by the events caused by a tornado of which he was trying to save his daughter from. The only way for him to wake up and set things right is for him (or for you) to get to the Thalamus, what in his mind manifests as a gigantic tree on the horizon. So while he travles through his own mind he learns about himself, the decisions he made, the way he repeated the mistakes his father did and the way to forgive oneself. The story is actually really well written and beautiful and it would have really touched me if it wasn't for one thing:The voice acting and narrating. I do not know if only I feel this way or if others share my opinion but I would not have picked Greg Nugent as the voice actor for this game. I don't suggest he does a bad job, quite the opposite actually. You can hear, that he puts his heart into it. His voice just does not fit the character and the more I played, the more I got anoyed with it. Furthermore there are technical flaws. Some of the words he says are poorly pronounced, the mic overrides or pops at some points which is not only distrubing the atmosphere, but is also unprofessionell. I do not claim, that I could do it any better and it should be noted again that Mind is an indie title, but to write a propper review I have to adress this point.Now for the last topic I would like to point out: the sound and music.One reason for me to buy Mind: Path to Thalamus was actually the Music as heard in the trailer. I thought that if they had such a fitting track picked for their advertisement, the music in game would have been just as good. And I was not disappointed. The soundeffects, the music, as well as the overall ambience was very satisfactory and including the voice acting, very well balanced. But there is one thing, that I thought negatively of, which is the fact that the developers did not implement a way to regulate the volume. Even though I think it was on purpose it is a fact, that the game on default is brutally loud, which actually makes for some mild jumpscares, when the character suddenly starts to talk.So now comes the difficult part: the rating.Graphics: Given the fact that the game is built on the Unreal Engine and given the budget this indie title probably recieved you could not ask for more [10/10]Gameplay: The Steam description of the game claims that the title has more than it actually features. Still, there was a lot of thought put into these puzzles and the gameplay is more than average though negatively effected through leveldesign [7/10]Leveldesign: Bumps the gameplay noticably but supports the artistic design of the game [4/10]Story: Enjoyable, solid storytelling and narrating but affected through bad voice acting and a bit bumpy at the end [7/10]Voice Acting: Under average acting with minor technical problems, though not totally effortless [3/10]Sound, music and ambiance: Brilliant music and ambiance with good soundeffects [9/10]Overall rating: Mind: Path to Thalamus is not a ""Must have played"" title. It is a good game and an exellent indie game. I recomend it to anyone who likes visually beautiful games with a nice story and does not mind a little bumpy voice acting or a bit running around. I cannot say it is worth the money you would spend for it, that depends on how much you earn, how much you can spare for games and on your personal taste in games. For me this game was definetely worth it[7/10]Thanks for reading, I hope it was helpful."
